<subSubSection id="D9C76503FFFAFFD6FF04E854FEBAFB6E" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494" type="description">
<paragraph id="91623688FFFAFFD6FF04E854FE04FD37" blockId="15.[178,1086,577,657]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">
Redescription: Body length 
<quantity id="56259B6DFFFAFFD6FDE5E854FD3AFDF0" box="[595,722,577,599]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.15" metricValueMax="6.5" metricValueMin="5.8" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494" unit="mm" value="6.15" valueMax="6.5" valueMin="5.8">5.8-6.5 mm</quantity>
; length of forebody 3.0- 
<quantity id="56259B6DFFFAFFD6FC55E854FBD2FDF0" box="[995,1082,577,599]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494" unit="mm" value="3.1">3.1 mm</quantity>
. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation id="09E62A0DFFFAFFD6FEFFE84BFE63FDD2" box="[329,395,606,628]" captionStart="Figs 9-16" captionStartId="14.[178,218,1520,1540]" captionTargetBox="[182,1076,213,1487]" captionTargetId="figure-58@14.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 9-16: Micrillus aethiopicus (CAMERON), paratype (9-13) and M. nigriceps (CAMERON), lectotype (14-16): (9) habitus; (10) forebody; (11, 14) male sternite VIII; (12-13, 15-16) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 9-10: 1.0 mm; 11-16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5301295" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5301295/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
. Coloration: head reddish to blackish-brown; remainder of body, including appendages, reddish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="91623688FFFAFFD6FF04E8B5FD3CFC8A" blockId="15.[178,1085,672,812]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">
Head (
<figureCitation id="09E62A0DFFFAFFD6FF4FE8B5FEAEFD10" box="[249,326,672,694]" captionStart="Figs 9-16" captionStartId="14.[178,218,1520,1540]" captionTargetBox="[182,1076,213,1487]" captionTargetId="figure-58@14.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 9-16: Micrillus aethiopicus (CAMERON), paratype (9-13) and M. nigriceps (CAMERON), lectotype (14-16): (9) habitus; (10) forebody; (11, 14) male sternite VIII; (12-13, 15-16) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 9-10: 1.0 mm; 11-16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5301295" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5301295/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
) approximately 1.08 times as long as broad, broadest across eyes, narrowed behind eyes; posterior angles rather weakly marked, rounded; punctation sparse and fine; integument with extremely shallow microsculpture. Eyes nearly as long as postocular region in dorsal view. Antenna long and slender, approximately 
<quantity id="56259B6DFFFAFFD6FC02E8EDFBEAFCA8" box="[948,1026,760,782]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494" unit="mm" value="2.6">2.6 mm</quantity>
long; antennomere X approximately twice as long as broad.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="91623688FFFAFFD6FF04E929FEB9FC2D" blockId="15.[178,1085,827,907]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="09E62A0DFFFAFFD6FE91E92EFE9BFCF7" box="[295,371,827,849]" captionStart="Figs 9-16" captionStartId="14.[178,218,1520,1540]" captionTargetBox="[182,1076,213,1487]" captionTargetId="figure-58@14.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 9-16: Micrillus aethiopicus (CAMERON), paratype (9-13) and M. nigriceps (CAMERON), lectotype (14-16): (9) habitus; (10) forebody; (11, 14) male sternite VIII; (12-13, 15-16) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 9-10: 1.0 mm; 11-16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5301295" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5301295/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
) approximately 1.15 times as long as broad and 1.05-1.10 times as broad as head; punctation very fine and very dense; interstices without distinct microsculpture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="91623688FFFAFFD6FF04E98EFC69FC4D" blockId="15.[178,1085,923,1003]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">
Elytra (
<figureCitation id="09E62A0DFFFAFFD6FF48E98EFEA0FC17" box="[254,328,923,945]" captionStart="Figs 9-16" captionStartId="14.[178,218,1520,1540]" captionTargetBox="[182,1076,213,1487]" captionTargetId="figure-58@14.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 9-16: Micrillus aethiopicus (CAMERON), paratype (9-13) and M. nigriceps (CAMERON), lectotype (14-16): (9) habitus; (10) forebody; (11, 14) male sternite VIII; (12-13, 15-16) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 9-10: 1.0 mm; 11-16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5301295" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5301295/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
) approximately as long as pronotum; punctation very fine and very dense; surface nearly matt. Hind wings fully developed. Protarsomeres I-IV not dilated. Metatarsomere I approximately as long as the combined length of II and III.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="91623688FFFAFFD6FF04E9EEFC8AFB88" blockId="15.[178,1085,1019,1070]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">Abdomen distinctly narrower than elytra; punctation fine and very dense; interstices with microsculpture; posterior margin of tergite VII with palisade fringe.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="91623688FFFAFFD6FF71EE2BFEBAFB6E" blockId="15.[178,1086,1085,1224]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">
: sternite VIII (
<figureCitation id="09E62A0DFFFAFFD6FECEEE28FE21FBF5" box="[376,457,1085,1107]" captionStart="Figs 9-16" captionStartId="14.[178,218,1520,1540]" captionTargetBox="[182,1076,213,1487]" captionTargetId="figure-58@14.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 9-16: Micrillus aethiopicus (CAMERON), paratype (9-13) and M. nigriceps (CAMERON), lectotype (14-16): (9) habitus; (10) forebody; (11, 14) male sternite VIII; (12-13, 15-16) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 9-10: 1.0 mm; 11-16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5301295" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5301295/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
) strongly oblong, posterior excision narrowly V-shaped; aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="09E62A0DFFFAFFD6FEA9EE4FFE78FBD6" box="[287,400,1114,1136]" captionStart="Figs 9-16" captionStartId="14.[178,218,1520,1540]" captionTargetBox="[182,1076,213,1487]" captionTargetId="figure-58@14.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 9-16: Micrillus aethiopicus (CAMERON), paratype (9-13) and M. nigriceps (CAMERON), lectotype (14-16): (9) habitus; (10) forebody; (11, 14) male sternite VIII; (12-13, 15-16) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 9-10: 1.0 mm; 11-16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5301295" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5301295/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">Figs 12-13</figureCitation>
) approximately 
<quantity id="56259B6DFFFAFFD6FD8DEE4FFD63FBD6" box="[571,651,1114,1136]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494" unit="mm" value="0.7">0.7 mm</quantity>
long, strongly asymmetric, and of highly distinctive morphology; ventral process strongly inflected dorsad; internal sac with long, slender, and curved sclerotized spines, one of them apically extending beyond apex of ventral process.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D9C76503FFFAFFD6FF04EEC2FCADF9EE" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="91623688FFFAFFD6FF04EEC2FEEEFAC5" blockId="15.[178,1086,1239,1379]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">
Comparative notes: As can be inferred from the similar external characters and from the morphology of the male sexual characters, 
<taxonomicName id="56DD4D0BFFFAFFD6FD4AEEE3FC7CFAAD" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2013" baseAuthorityName="Cameron" baseAuthorityYear="1947" box="[764,916,1269,1291]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Micrillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aethiopicus">
<emphasis id="A3A9EA9AFFFAFFD6FD4AEEE3FC7CFAAD" box="[764,916,1269,1291]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">M. aethiopicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely allied to 
<taxonomicName id="56DD4D0BFFFAFFD6FF7AEF06FDDDFA8E" authority="(BERNHAUER 1910)" baseAuthorityName="BERNHAUER" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[204,565,1298,1320]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Micrillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aegyptiacus">
<emphasis id="A3A9EA9AFFFAFFD6FF7AEF06FE80FA8E" box="[204,360,1299,1320]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">M. aegyptiacus</emphasis>
(BERNHAUER 1910)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="56DD4D0BFFFAFFD6FDD1EF06FC96FA8E" authority="ASSING 2008" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2008" box="[615,894,1298,1320]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Micrillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sudanicus">
<emphasis id="A3A9EA9AFFFAFFD6FDD1EF06FD07FA8E" box="[615,751,1298,1320]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">M. sudanicus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="F54C4B79FFFAFFD6FD43EF07FC96FA8E" author="ASSING V" box="[757,894,1298,1320]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494" pagination="301 - 344" refId="ref22718" refString="ASSING V. (2008): A revision of the Micrillus species of the Palaearctic region, with notes on two species from adjacent parts of the Afrotropical and Oriental regions (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae). - Stuttgarter Beitrage zur Naturkunde Serie A, Neue Serie 1: 301 - 344." type="journal article" year="2008">ASSING 2008</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. It is distinguished from both of them particularly by the morphology of the aedeagus and additionally as follows:
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="91623688FFFAFFD6FF04EF67FE46FA64" blockId="15.[178,1085,1394,1474]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">
from 
<taxonomicName id="56DD4D0BFFFAFFD6FF5DEF66FE6FFA2E" box="[235,391,1395,1416]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Micrillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aegyptiacus">
<emphasis id="A3A9EA9AFFFAFFD6FF5DEF66FE6FFA2E" box="[235,391,1395,1416]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">M. aegyptiacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by larger eyes, the relatively smaller and narrower head, the much denser and more distinct punctation of the pronotum, and the narrower posterior excision of the male sternite VIII;
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="91623688FFFAFFD6FF04EFC7FD81F9A3" blockId="15.[178,1085,1490,1541]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">
from 
<taxonomicName id="56DD4D0BFFFAFFD6FF5BEFC6FE9FFA4E" box="[237,375,1490,1512]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Micrillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sudanicus">
<emphasis id="A3A9EA9AFFFAFFD6FF5BEFC6FE9FFA4E" box="[237,375,1490,1512]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">M. sudanicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the relatively smaller head, the smaller eyes, and the less deep posterior excision of the male sternite VIII.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="91623688FFFAFFD6FF04EC01FCADF9EE" blockId="15.[178,1085,1556,1608]" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">
Distribution and natural history: This species is currently known only from several localities in southern 
<collectingCountry id="E9CA7618FFFAFFD6FD26EC27FD0EF9EE" box="[656,742,1586,1608]" name="Ethiopia" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">Ethiopia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="09E62A0DFFFAFFD6FD45EC27FCD0F9EE" box="[755,824,1586,1608]" captionStart="Map 2" captionStartId="12.[178,223,1191,1211]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,212,1169]" captionTargetId="figure-224@12.[178,1085,212,1169]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Map 2: Distributions of Micrillus aegyptiacus (BERNHAUER) (circles), M. sudanicus ASSING (triangles), and M. aethiopicus (CAMERON) (diamonds; open diamonds unrevised records; unidentified locality &quot;Nargi&quot; omitted)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6511858" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6511858/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="1494">Map 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
